related_questions.question: Is strawberry jam better with or without pectin?
related_questions.snippet: It's equally as satisfying to take those sweet berries home and make homemade jam. There's no pectin added — the generations-old recipe I use doesn't include it, and in my experience, it doesn't need it. Pectin is merely a thickening agent, it's used to give that jelly-like texture and consistency.

related_questions.question: Why add lemon juice when making strawberry jam?
related_questions.snippet: Adding acid in the form of fresh lemon or lime juice is important for two reasons: First, it makes for a more well-balanced jam, returning some of the acidity lost with the addition of sugar. Second, pectin needs acid to properly activate, or firm up.

related_questions.question: What is the difference between strawberry jam and strawberry jelly?
related_questions.snippet: Jam or preserves will contain the richest portions of fruitiness, while a jelly's flavor will be slightly bogged down by the gelatin. This is why preserves are often called for in cooking and baking, as they contain the largest amount of the fruit's flavor in a mixable form.

buttons.subtitle: What Is Jam Made Of
buttons.title: The Difference Between Jam, Jelly, and Other Fruit Preserves
buttons.snippet: Jam is made from fruit, sugar, pectin, and acid (such as lemon or other fruit juice). Most often, the fruit used to make jam is chopped or crushed and then slowly cooked with sugar until it thickens. Jam is regulated by the FDA; it must come from a single fruit and contain at least 45% fruit and 55% sugar.
